SIMPLE: effeminate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Effeminate
<hw>Ef*fem"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>effeminatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>effeminare</ets> to make a woman
of; <ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>femina</ets> a woman. See
<er>Feminine</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having some
characteristic of a woman, as delicacy, luxuriousness, etc.; soft or
delicate to an unmanly degree; womanish; weak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king, by his voluptuous life and mean marriage, became
<qex>effeminate</qex>, and less sensible of honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>effeminate</qex> and unmanly foppery.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hurd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Womanlike; womanly; tender; -- in a good
sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gentle, kind, <qex>effeminate</qex> remorse.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Effeminate</xex> and <xex>womanish</xex> are
generally used in a reproachful sense; <xex>feminine</xex> and
<xex>womanly</xex>, applied to women, are epithets of propriety or
commendation.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effeminate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Effeminate
<hw>Ef*fem"i*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Effeminated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Effeminating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To
make womanish; to make soft and delicate; to weaken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will not corrupt or <qex>effeminate</qex> children's minds.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effeminate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Effeminate
<hw>Ef*fem"i*nate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow womanish or
weak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In a slothful peace both courage will <qex>effeminate</qex> and
manners corrupt.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effeminately</ent>⟦br⟧
